      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mothers Against Guns</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elton Glaser III letter comments on May 7 Week in Review article on planned Million Mom March against gun violence in Washington and other cities (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One striking thing about the Million Mom March participants you describe in ''Invoking the Moral Authority of Moms'' (Week in Review, May 7) is that they were galvanized by Columbine and similar suburban tragedies. Why should the moral authority of mothers in the inner city (whose children are far more susceptible to gun violence) be any less powerful?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One striking thing about the Million Mom March participants you describe in ''Invoking the Moral Authority of Moms'' (Week in Review, May 7) is that they were galvanized by Columbine and similar suburban tragedies. Why should the moral authority of mothers in the inner city (whose children are far more susceptible to gun violence) be any less powerful?</p>
        <p>It is reflective of the power gap in our society that it takes a Columbine tragedy to bring serious attention to gun control when fatal shootings have been plaguing urban families for many years. One would hope that any resulting legislation will be effective against gun violence in both urban and suburban settings.</p>
        <p>ELTON GLASER III  Chicago, May 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
